SIMPLE: obsequious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Obsequious
<hw>Ob*se"qui*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>obsequiosus</ets>, fr. <ets>obsequium</ets> compliance, fr.
<ets>obsequi</ets>, fr. <ets>obsequi</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>obs⟦eacute⟧quieux</ets>, See <er>Obsequent</er>, and cf.
<er>Obsequy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Promptly obedient, or
submissive, to the will of another; compliant; yielding to the desires
of another; devoted.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His servants weeping,⟦br⟧
<qex>Obsequious</qex> to his orders, bear him hither.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Servilely or meanly attentive; compliant to excess;
cringing; fawning; <as>as, <ex>obsequious</ex> flatterer,
parasite</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There lies ever in ⟦ldquo⟧<qex>obsequious</qex>⟦rdquo⟧ at the
present the sense of an observance which is overdone, of an unmanly
readiness to fall in with the will of another.</q>
<rj><qau>Trench.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <ety>[See <er>Obsequy</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining
to obsequies; funereal.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧To do
<xex>obsequious</xex> sorrow.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Compliant; obedient; servile. See
<er>Yielding</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Obsequiously</ent>⟦br⟧
